Indicator: Infant mortality rate (deaths per 1,000 live births)
Definition: Number of all infant deaths (within first year of life) per 1,000 live births. Rate is calculated as the average rate across five years.
Source: Centers for Disease Control and Prevention

Definition: Number of youth deaths ages 1-17 per 100,000. Rate is calculated as the average rate across five years.
Source: Centers for Disease Control and Prevention

Definition: Percentage of children under six with blood lead levels greater then 4.5 micrograms per deciliter
Prevalance of vaccine-preventable diseases per 10,000 population, 2015-2017 average

Percentage of people in a county with low income, and living more than 1 mile from a supermarket, supercenter or large grocery store, if in an urban area, or more than 10 miles from a supermarket or large grocery store if in a rural area.

Indicator: Contaminated drinking water (contaminant concentration over one compliance cycle)
Definition: County-level average of the sum of water contaminant concentrations within each census tract over one compliance cycle (2005-2013). Contaminants include Arsenic, cadmium, chromium, dibromochloropropane (DBCP), lead, nitrate, perchlorate, radium 226, radium 228, total trihalomethanes (THM), tetrachloroethylene, trichloroethylene (TCE), trichloropropane, and uranium.
Source: CalEnviroScreen 3.0 - California Office of Environmental Health Hazard Assessment (OEHHA)

Definition: County-level average of water gallons per day per capita delivered by each water system. Water system delivery totals are calculated on a monthly basis, divided by the number of days per month and transformed to per capita based on the size of the population serviced.
Source: California State Water Resources Control Board

Indicator: Groundwater pollutants (sum of weighted site scores)
Definition: County-level average of the sum of weighted scores for groundwater contamination sites within each census tract. Scores within each census tract are weighted based on operation status that is affected by pollutant levels and adjusted by distance from population. Pollutants include: gasoline and diesel fuels, chlorinated solvents and other volatile organic compounds (VOCs) such as benzene, toluene, and methyl tert-butyl ether (MTBE); heavy metals such as lead, chromium and arsenic; polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons (PAHs); persistent organic pollutants like polychlorinated biphenyls (PCBs); DDT and other insecticides; and perchlorate.
Source: CalEnviroScreen 3.0 - California Office of Environmental Health Hazard Assessment (OEHHA)

Indicator: Solid waste sites (sum of weighted site scores)
Definition:
County-level average of the sum of the adjusted
weights for sites each census tract within the county contains or is near. Solid waste sites and facilities are weighted on a scale of 1 to a maximum of 13 in consideration of both the site type and violation history; the weighted scores of all facilities in an area are then summed after adjusting for proximity to population.
Source: CalEnviroScreen 3.0 - California Office of Environmental Health Hazard Assessment (OEHHA)

Definition: Number of cases per 100,000 jurisdiction population per year.
Percentage of households with more than one occupant per room

Indicator: Housing cost burden (owners) (% of housing units)
Definition: Fraction of owned housing units with cost greater than 30% of household income

Indicator: Housing cost burden (renters) (% of housing units)
Definition: Fraction of rented housing units with cost greater than 30% of household income

Indicator: Outstanding regional housing needs allocation (RHNA) (% of construction permits)
Definition: % of construction permits outstanding to meet Regional Housing Needs Assessment as reported to California Department of Housing and Community Development as required by law.
Source: California Department of Housing and Community Development

Definition: Percent of total population that is homeless, as collected by Housing and Urban Development Continuum of Care (CoC). In cases where one county has multiple CoCs, the county figure is the sum of these estimates. In cases where one CoC covers multiple counties, the count is population-weighted among the covered counties.
Source: US Department of Housing and Urban Development; SPI calculation

Definition: Number of motor vehicle deaths per 100,000 population, age-standardized.
Source: Centers for Disease Control and Prevention

Indicator: Property crime rate (per 100,000 pop.; five-year average)
Definition: Five-year average cleared property crime rate per 100,000 population.
Five-year average cleared homicide rate per 100,000 population.
Five-year average cleared forcible rape rate per 100,000 population. .
Percent of 3 to 4 year olds enrolled in school, public or private

Indicator: Third grade language arts proficiency (% of 3rd graders)
Definition: Percent of third graders meeting or exceeding CAASPP standards in Language Arts. County-level data are calculated as the average of percent met or exceeding standards among schools within the county.

Indicator: Eighth grade math proficiency (% of 8th graders)
Definition: Percent of eighth graders meeting or exceeding CAASPP standards in Mathematics. County-level data are calculated as the average of percent met or exceeding standards among schools within the county.

Indicator: Less than 9th grade education (% of pop. age 25+)
Definition: Percent of population age 25+ with less than 9th grade education

Indicator: Population without high school education (% of pop. ages 18-24 without high school diploma or equivalent)
Web hover Definition: (% of pop. ages 18-24 without high school diploma or equivalent)
Definition: Percent of population aged 18-24 without high school diploma or equivalent

Indicator: Broadband adoption rate (% of connections per housing units offered connection)
Web hover Definition: (% of connections per housing units offered connection)
Definition: Percentage of consumer broadband connections per housing units offered broadband connection

Indicator: Slow or no broadband service (% of households)
Definition: Percentage of total households with slow broadband service (<6 Mbps down or <1 Mbps up) or no broadband service.
Number of public library visits per capita. County-level data on library visits are calculated as the sum of all visits to all libraries within a county. Data are drawn from fiscal year 2016-2017.

Indicator: Premature deaths (years of life lost before age 75 per 100,000 pop.; age-adjusted)
Web hover Definition: (years of life lost before age 75 per 100,000 pop.; age-adjusted)
Definition: Years of potential life lost before age 75 per 100,000 population, age-adjusted.

Indicator: Poor mental health days (average days per month)
Definition: The average number of days a county’s adult respondents report that their mental health was not good, based on the survey question: “Thinking about your mental health, which includes stress, depression, and problems with emotions, for how many days during the past 30 days was your mental health not good?”. The measure is age-adjusted to the 2000 US population.
Percentage of adults that report a BMI of 30 or more.
Percentage of adults aged 20 and above with diagnosed diabetes.

Indicator: Drug overdose deaths (deaths per 100,000 pop.; age-adjusted)
Definition: Number of drug poisoning deaths per 100,000 population, age-adjusted. Includes both intentional self-poisoning and accidental poisoning, as well as undetermined intent.
Source: Centers for Disease Control and Prevention

Definition: Mean of summer months (May-October) of the daily maximum 8-hour ozone concentration (ppm), averaged over three years
Source: CalEnviroScreen 3.0 - California Office of Environmental Health Hazard Assessment (OEHHA)

Definition: Annual mean concentration of PM2.5 (average of quarterly means, μg/m3), over three years
Source: CalEnviroScreen 3.0 - California Office of Environmental Health Hazard Assessment (OEHHA)

Definition: County-level average of the sum of traffic volumes adjusted by road segment length (vehicle-kilometers per hour) divided by total road length (kilometers) within 150 meters of the census tract boundary
Source: CalEnviroScreen 3.0 - California Office of Environmental Health Hazard Assessment (OEHHA)

Definition: Average total household CO2 emissions in metric tons (electricity, housing, food, and transportation)

Indicator: Wildfire vulnerability (index of wildfire potential and social vulnerability)
Web hover Definition: (index of wildfire potential and social vulnerability)
Definition: Index of wildfire potential and social vulnerability
Source: Davies et al 2018 analysis; US Forest Service & American Community Survey data

Definition: Total voter registrations divided by voting eligible population in the 2016 General Election
Total number of voters divided by voting eligible population in the 2016 General Election
Rate of complaints against peace officers per 100,000 population. County-level complaint data are calculated as the average number of complaints among all precincts within each county per year.
Percentage of households that are owner-occupied.

Indicator: Teen births (births per 1,000 female pop. ages 15-19)
Definition: Number of births per 1,000 female population ages 15-19.

Indicator: Access to exercise opportunities (% of pop.)
Definition: The percentage of population who live reasonably close (at the census block level, defined as within one mile in urban blocks and within three miles in rural blocks) to a location for physical activity. Locations for physical activity are defined as parks or recreational facilities. Parks include local, state, and national parks. Recreational facilities include YMCAs as well as businesses such as gyms, community centers, dance studios and pools.

Percentage of total population living in a census tract designated as a child care desert. Child care desert is defined by the Center for American Progress as a census tract with 50 or more children under 5 where there is no child care provider or where the ratio of children under age five to the cumulative childcare capacity is more than 3 to 1.
Source: California Department of Social Services & American Community Survey 5-year

Definition: Percentage of teens and young adults ages 16-24 who are neither working nor in school.

The isolation index measures the extent to which minorities are exposed only to one another. It is calculated as the
minority-weighted average of the minority proportion in each county.
Source: American Community Survey; SPI calculations; Iceland, J., Weinberg, D., and Steinmetz E. (2002). Racial and Ethnic Residential Segregation in the United States: 1980-2000. U.S. Census Bureau, Series CENSR-3

Definition: Residential segregation is the index of dissimilarity where higher values indicate greater residential segregation between non-white and white county residents. The residential segregation index ranges from 0 (complete integration) to 100 (complete segregation)
Source: American Community Survey; SPI calculations; Iceland, J., Weinberg, D., and Steinmetz E. (2002). Racial and Ethnic Residential Segregation in the United States: 1980-2000. U.S. Census Bureau, Series CENSR-3

Definition: Number of hate crimes per 100,000 of population

Rate of allegations of harrassment or bullying based on sex, race, disability status, sexual orientation, or religion per 100,000 students enrolled. Number of allegations are reported at the school district levels for all public schools and are then aggregated to county total.

Indicator: Female county supervisors (% of county supervisors)
Definition: Percent of female county supervisors
Households in which no one 14 and over speaks English only or speaks a language other than English at home and speaks English very well

Indicator: College or graduate school enrollment (% of pop. age 15+)
Definition: Percent of population age 15 and over enrolled in college or graduate school

Indicator: Associates degree holders (% of pop. age 25+)
Definition: Percent of population 25 and older whose highest degree attained is an Associate's degree

Indicator: Bachelors degree holders (% of pop. age 25+)
Definition: Percent of population 25 and older whose highest degree attained is a Bachelor's degree

Indicator: Advanced degree holders (% of pop. age 25+)
Definition: Percent of population 25 and older whose highest degree attained is a Master's, professional school degree, or Doctorate.
